.TH RESMAN 8 "April 2026" "v1.23.0" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
resman \- Dynamic CPU/RAM/IO resource manager for Linux using cgroups v2
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B resman
[\fB\-\-config\fR \fIFILE\fR]
[\fB\-\-version\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B resman
is a daemon that monitors system CPU and RAM usage and dynamically applies limits to users
when the load exceeds configured thresholds. It uses Linux cgroups v2 to manage
CPU resource distribution efficiently and proportionally.
.PP
The daemon operates in control cycles configured via
.B POLLING_INTERVAL
and makes decisions based on configurable thresholds to enable or disable CPU limits.
.SH FEATURES
.IP \(bu 2
Dynamic CPU limiting based on configurable thresholds
.IP \(bu
Dynamic RAM limiting with soft/hard limits (memory.high/memory.max)
.IP \(bu
IO bandwidth and IOPS limiting (io.max)
.IP \(bu
Automatic user detection and cgroup management
.IP \(bu
Blackout timeframes support (BLACKOUT)
.IP \(bu
User filtering with regex support (USER_INCLUDE_LIST, USER_EXCLUDE_LIST)
.IP \(bu
Process exclusion list (PROCESS_EXCLUDE_LIST)
.IP \(bu
Threshold time window to prevent false activations (CPU_THRESHOLD_DURATION)
.IP \(bu
Username resolution cache for improved performance (USERNAME_CACHE_TTL)
.IP \(bu
SQLite metrics database for historical data (METRICS_DB_*)
.IP \(bu
MCP server with 15 tools for AI assistant integration
.IP \(bu
Prometheus metrics export with hostname and server_role labels
.IP \(bu
LDAP/NIS username resolution support (requires CGO)
.IP \(bu
Workload pattern detection for adaptive limits (AUTODETECT_PATTERNS)
.IP \(bu
IO starvation auto\-remediation (IO_REMEDIATION_ENABLED)
.IP \(bu
Timeout configuration for cgroup operations (CGROUP_OPERATION_TIMEOUT)
.IP \(bu
Performance optimizations: gopsutil process scanning, batch PID moves, regex cache
.IP \(bu
Graceful shutdown with proper resource cleanup
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-config\fR \fIFILE\fR
Specifies the configuration file path. Default:
.I /etc/resman.conf
.TP
\fB\-\-version\fR
Displays program version and exits.
.SH ARCHITECTURE AND CPU ALLOCATION
The system uses a cgroups v2 hierarchy to manage fair CPU resource distribution:
.IP 1. 3
Calculates available cores for users:
.I Total cores \- MIN_SYSTEM_CORES
.IP 2.
Creates a parent (shared) cgroup with the calculated total quota
.IP 3.
For each active user, creates a sub\-cgroup with equal
.B cpu.weight
.IP 4.
User processes are moved to their respective sub\-cgroups
.PP
Resource division occurs proportionally through cgroup
.B cpu.weight
values. If a user doesn't use CPU, other users can utilize more than their
fair share, up to the entire available quota.
.PP
Practical example with 4 total cores and MIN_SYSTEM_CORES=2:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Available cores for users: 2
.IP \(bu
2 active users \(-> each user gets weight 100
.IP \(bu
If User1 uses 0.5 cores, User2 can use 1.5 cores
.IP \(bu
If User1 uses no CPU, User2 can use all 2 cores
.RE
.SH RAM LIMITS
When enabled, the daemon monitors total memory usage by non\-system users and applies limits when the configured threshold is exceeded.
.PP
RAM limiting uses cgroups v2 memory controller with two levels of control:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B memory.max
- hard limit (processes will be OOM\-killed if exceeded)
.IP \(bu
.B memory.high
- soft limit (memory pressure triggers reclaim, processes may throttle)
.RE
.PP
Configuration parameters:
.IP \(bu 2
.B RAM_LIMIT_ENABLED
- Enable RAM limiting (true/false)
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_THRESHOLD
- Activation threshold percentage of total user RAM usage
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_RELEASE_THRESHOLD
- Deactivation threshold percentage
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_QUOTA_LIMITED
- Total RAM limit when limits are active (bytes or K/M/G/T suffix)
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_QUOTA_PER_USER
- Per\-user RAM limit (when limits active)
.IP \(bu
.B DISABLE_SWAP
- Set memory.swap.max=0 to prevent swap usage (true/false)
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_HIGH_RATIO
- Ratio between memory.high and memory.max (0.0\-1.0, default 0.8)
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_USER_INCLUDE_LIST
- Regex patterns for users subject to RAM limits (empty = all)
.IP \(bu
.B RAM_USER_EXCLUDE_LIST
- Regex patterns for users excluded from RAM limits
.PP
When RAM limits are active, each user's cgroup receives both
.B memory.max
and
.B memory.high
limits according to the configured quotas and ratio.
.SH IO LIMITS
When enabled, the daemon monitors I/O usage and applies bandwidth and IOPS limits via cgroups v2 io controller.
.PP
IO limiting supports both bandwidth (bytes per second) and IOPS (operations per second) limits for read and write operations independently.
.PP
Configuration parameters:
.IP \(bu 2
.B IO_LIMIT_ENABLED
- Enable IO limiting (true/false)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_THRESHOLD
- Activation threshold percentage of total user I/O usage
.IP \(bu
.B IO_RELEASE_THRESHOLD
- Deactivation threshold percentage
.IP \(bu
.B IO_READ_BPS
- Read bandwidth limit (e.g., "100M", "1G")
.IP \(bu
.B IO_WRITE_BPS
- Write bandwidth limit
.IP \(bu
.B IO_READ_IOPS
- Read IOPS limit (0 = unlimited)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_WRITE_IOPS
- Write IOPS limit (0 = unlimited)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_DEVICE_FILTER
- Device specification ("all" or "major:minor")
.IP \(bu
.B IO_THRESHOLD_DURATION
- Seconds to wait before activating IO limits (0 = immediate)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_USER_INCLUDE_LIST
- Regex patterns for users subject to IO limits (empty = all)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_USER_EXCLUDE_LIST
- Regex patterns for users excluded from IO limits
.PP
IO starvation auto\-remediation can be enabled to temporarily boost limits when processes experience excessive throttling:
.IP \(bu 2
.B IO_REMEDIATION_ENABLED
- Enable auto\-remediation (true/false)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_STARVATION_THRESHOLD
- Seconds of continuous throttling before remediation
.IP \(bu
.B IO_BOOST_MULTIPLIER
- Multiplier for temporary limits (e.g., 2.0 = double)
.IP \(bu
.B IO_BOOST_DURATION
- Duration of boost in seconds
.IP \(bu
.B IO_BOOST_MAX_PER_HOUR
- Maximum boosts per user per hour
.IP \(bu
.B IO_PSI_THRESHOLD
- PSI some avg10 % threshold for detection
.IP \(bu
.B IO_REVERT_ON_NORMAL
- Revert limits when I/O returns to normal (true/false)
.PP
.SH WORKLOAD PATTERN DETECTION
When enabled, the daemon analyzes historical CPU and RAM usage patterns to automatically classify users as "batch" (night\-time high resource consumption) or "interactive" (day\-time moderate usage) and applies appropriate quotas.
.PP
The pattern detection algorithm uses a sliding window of
.B PATTERN_HISTORY_HOURS
hours and requires at least
.B PATTERN_MIN_SAMPLES
data points before making decisions. Classification confidence must exceed
.B PATTERN_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD
(0.0\-1.0).
.PP
Detected patterns influence resource allocation:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B Batch night
- Users with high resource usage during night hours receive higher CPU quota (
.B BATCH_NIGHT_CPU_QUOTA
) and RAM quota (
.B BATCH_NIGHT_RAM_QUOTA
).
.IP \(bu
.B Interactive day
- Users with moderate daytime usage receive standard quotas (
.B INTERACTIVE_CPU_QUOTA
,
.B INTERACTIVE_RAM_QUOTA
).
.RE
.PP
Configuration parameters:
.IP \(bu 2
.B AUTODETECT_PATTERNS
- Enable automatic pattern detection (true/false)
.IP \(bu
.B PATTERN_HISTORY_HOURS
- Historical window in hours (default: 168 = 1 week)
.IP \(bu
.B PATTERN_MIN_SAMPLES
- Minimum samples required for classification
.IP \(bu
.B PATTERN_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD
- Confidence threshold (0.0\-1.0)
.IP \(bu
.B BATCH_NIGHT_CPU_QUOTA
- CPU quota for batch users (microseconds, e.g., 200000 = 2 cores)
.IP \(bu
.B BATCH_NIGHT_RAM_QUOTA
- RAM quota for batch users (bytes or suffix)
.IP \(bu
.B INTERACTIVE_CPU_QUOTA
- CPU quota for interactive users
.IP \(bu
.B INTERACTIVE_RAM_QUOTA
- RAM quota for interactive users
.PP
Pattern detection runs hourly and updates user classifications automatically.
.SH CONTROL CYCLE
The daemon executes control cycles at regular intervals:
.IP 1. 3
Collects system metrics (total CPU usage, per\-user CPU, load average)
.IP 2.
Decision making based on configured thresholds
.IP 3.
Applying/removing limits via cgroups
.IP 4.
Logging and Prometheus metrics update (if enabled)
.SH PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATIONS
The daemon incorporates several performance optimizations to minimize overhead on managed systems:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B gopsutil integration
- Efficient process scanning via the proven gopsutil library, replacing custom /proc parsing.
.IP \(bu
.B sync.Map regex cache
- Thread\-safe caching of compiled regular expressions for user filtering, eliminating race conditions.
.IP \(bu
.B Batch PID moves
- Grouping process ID migrations during cgroup cleanup to reduce system call overhead.
.IP \(bu
.B Consolidated /proc scans
- Single scan of /proc for all user metrics, reducing I/O operations by ~70%.
.IP \(bu
.B Sharded mutexes
- Fine\-grained locking for per\-process CPU tracking to minimize contention.
.IP \(bu
.B Pre\-allocated slices
- Estimated capacity allocation for dynamic slices to reduce heap allocations.
.IP \(bu
.B Intelligent cache invalidation
- Adaptive cache TTL based on system activity and user churn.
.RE
.PP
These optimizations ensure that monitoring overhead remains low even on systems with thousands of processes.
.SH CONFIGURATION FILE
The configuration file supports key=value format. Comments start with '#'.
Timeout parameters for cgroup operations, retry delays, and MCP shutdown can be configured to improve reliability in high\-load scenarios.
.PP
Example
.I /etc/resman.conf
format:
.nf
.sp
# =============================================
# RESMAN CONFIGURATION
# =============================================

# PATHS
CGROUP_ROOT="/sys/fs/cgroup"
CGROUP_BASE="resman"
CONFIG_FILE="/etc/resman.conf"
LOG_FILE="/var/log/resman.log"
CREATED_CGROUPS_FILE="/var/run/resman-cgroups.txt"
METRICS_CACHE_FILE="/var/run/resman-metrics.cache"
PROMETHEUS_FILE="/var/run/resman-metrics.prom"

# TIMING (seconds)
POLLING_INTERVAL=30          # Control cycle interval
MIN_ACTIVE_TIME=60           # Minimum activation time for limits
METRICS_CACHE_TTL=15         # Metrics cache duration

# TIMEOUT CONFIGURATION (seconds/milliseconds)
# CGROUP_OPERATION_TIMEOUT=5      # Timeout for cgroup operations (seconds)
# CGROUP_RETRY_DELAY_MS=100       # Delay between cgroup retry attempts (milliseconds)
# MCP_SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT=10         # Timeout for MCP server shutdown (seconds)

# CPU THRESHOLDS (percentage)
CPU_THRESHOLD=75             # Activation threshold
CPU_RELEASE_THRESHOLD=40     # Deactivation threshold

# CPU LIMITS ("quota period" format in microseconds)
CPU_QUOTA_NORMAL="max 100000"      # No limit (100000 = 100ms)
CPU_QUOTA_LIMITED="200000 100000"  # Limit: 2 core equivalents total

# RAM LIMITS
# RAM_LIMIT_ENABLED=false              # Enable RAM limiting via cgroups v2
# RAM_THRESHOLD=75                     # Percentage of total user RAM to activate limits
# RAM_RELEASE_THRESHOLD=40             # Percentage to release limits
# RAM_QUOTA_LIMITED=2G                 # Total RAM limit (bytes or K/M/G/T suffix)
# RAM_QUOTA_PER_USER=512M              # Per-user RAM limit (when limits active)
# DISABLE_SWAP=false                   # Set memory.swap.max=0 to prevent swap usage
# RAM_HIGH_RATIO=0.8                   # Ratio between memory.high and memory.max (0.0-1.0)

# IO LIMITS
# IO_LIMIT_ENABLED=false               # Enable IO limiting via cgroups v2 io controller
# IO_THRESHOLD=75                      # Percentage of total user IO to activate limits
# IO_RELEASE_THRESHOLD=40              # Percentage to release limits
# IO_READ_BPS=100M                     # Per-user read bandwidth limit (bytes/s)
# IO_WRITE_BPS=50M                     # Per-user write bandwidth limit
# IO_READ_IOPS=1000                    # Per-user read IOPS limit (0 = unlimited)
# IO_WRITE_IOPS=500                    # Per-user write IOPS limit
# IO_DEVICE_FILTER=all                 # "all" or "major:minor" device specification
# IO_THRESHOLD_DURATION=0              # Seconds to wait before activating IO limits

# LIMIT HOOK
LIMIT_HOOK_ENABLED=false               # Enable notification/action on newly limited users
# LIMIT_HOOK_SCRIPT=/usr/local/bin/resman-user-limited
# LIMIT_HOOK_URL=https://example.internal/resman/user-limited
LIMIT_HOOK_TIMEOUT=10                  # Hook timeout in seconds

# PROMETHEUS EXPORTER
ENABLE_PROMETHEUS=false                  # Enable metrics export
# PROMETHEUS_METRICS_BIND_HOST="0.0.0.0"   # Bind address (default: all interfaces)
# PROMETHEUS_METRICS_BIND_PORT=1974        # Port for metrics (default: 1974)
# Metrics available at: http://HOST:PORT/metrics

# PROMETHEUS TLS/HTTPS (optional)
PROMETHEUS_TLS_ENABLED=false            # Enable HTTPS/TLS
PROMETHEUS_TLS_CERT_FILE=/etc/resman/tls/server.crt    # Server certificate
PROMETHEUS_TLS_KEY_FILE=/etc/resman/tls/server.key     # Server private key
PROMETHEUS_TLS_CA_FILE=/etc/resman/tls/ca.crt          # CA certificate (optional)
PROMETHEUS_TLS_MIN_VERSION=1.2          # Minimum TLS version (1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3)

# PROMETHEUS AUTHENTICATION (optional)
PROMETHEUS_AUTH_TYPE="none"          # Authentication: none, basic, jwt, both
PROMETHEUS_AUTH_USERNAME="prometheus" # Username for Basic Auth
PROMETHEUS_AUTH_PASSWORD_FILE="/etc/resman/prometheus_password"  # Password file path
PROMETHEUS_JWT_SECRET_FILE="/etc/resman/jwt_secret"  # JWT secret file path
PROMETHEUS_JWT_ISSUER="resman"   # JWT issuer claim
PROMETHEUS_JWT_AUDIENCE="prometheus"  # JWT audience claim
PROMETHEUS_JWT_EXPIRY=3600            # JWT token expiry in seconds

# LOGGING
LOG_LEVEL="INFO"             # DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR
LOG_MAX_SIZE=10485760        # Maximum log file size (10MB)
USE_SYSLOG=true

# SYSTEM
MIN_SYSTEM_CORES=2           # Minimum cores reserved for system
SYSTEM_UID_MIN=1000          # Minimum UID for non\-system users
SYSTEM_UID_MAX=60000         # Maximum UID (default: pid_max)

# USER INCLUDE LIST (regex patterns, comma-separated)
# Only users matching these patterns are monitored
# USER_INCLUDE_LIST=^www.*,^apache.*    # Web users only
# USER_INCLUDE_LIST=francesco,www-data  # Specific users

# USER EXCLUDE LIST (usernames, comma-separated)
# These users are excluded from CPU limits
# USER_EXCLUDE_LIST=francesco,mysql     # Exclude specific users

# BLACKOUT TIMEFRAMES (when ResMan should NOT apply limits)
# Format: "days hours" (multiple timeframes separated by ;)
# Days: 0=Sunday, 1=Mon, 2=Tue, 3=Wed, 4=Thu, 5=Fri, 6=Sat
#       Or: * (all), 1-5 (Mon-Fri), 0,6 (weekend)
# Hours: 24h format (00-23)
#
# Examples:
# # Disable during business hours (Mon-Fri, 8-18)
# BLACKOUT=1-5 08-18
#
# # Disable only in the morning (Mon-Fri, 8-12)
# BLACKOUT=1-5 08-12
#
# # Disable on weekend (Sat-Sun, all day)
# BLACKOUT=0,6 00-23
#
# # Disable business hours + weekend
# BLACKOUT=1-5 08-18;0,6 00-23
#
# # Disable always (for testing)
# BLACKOUT=* 00-23
#
# # No blackout (default - Resource Manager always active)
BLACKOUT=

# LOAD AVERAGE CHECKING
IGNORE_SYSTEM_LOAD=false     # If true, ignores load average in decisions

# SERVER ROLE (optional)
SERVER_ROLE="database"       # Server role: database, web-frontend, batch, application, etc.

# MCP SERVER (Model Context Protocol)
MCP_ENABLED=false            # Enable MCP server for AI assistants
MCP_TRANSPORT="stdio"        # Transport: stdio, http
# MCP_HTTP_HOST="0.0.0.0"    # HTTP bind address (default: all interfaces)
# MCP_HTTP_PORT=1969         # HTTP port (default: 1969)
# MCP endpoint: http://HOST:PORT/mcp
MCP_LOG_LEVEL="INFO"         # MCP log level
MCP_AUTH_TOKEN="change-me"    # Optional Bearer token for HTTP transport
MCP_ALLOW_WRITE_OPS=false    # Allow write operations via MCP

# USERNAME CACHE (improves performance with LDAP/NIS)
# Cache TTL for UID to username resolution (minutes)
# Default: 60 minutes, Minimum: 1 minute
# Higher values reduce LDAP/NIS lookups but may delay username changes
USERNAME_CACHE_TTL=60

# METRICS DATABASE (SQLite for historical data via MCP)
# Enable persistent storage of metrics for historical queries
METRICS_DB_ENABLED=false
METRICS_DB_PATH=/etc/resman/metrics.db
METRICS_DB_RETENTION_DAYS=30      # How many days to keep data
METRICS_DB_WRITE_INTERVAL=30      # Write interval in seconds

# MCP TOOLS FOR HISTORICAL METRICS (when METRICS_DB_ENABLED=true):
# - get_user_history: Historical CPU/RAM for a user
# - get_system_history: Historical system metrics
# - get_user_summary: Aggregated statistics (avg/min/max)
# - get_metrics_database_info: Database status and info
.sp
.fi
.PP
A complete example configuration file with all available parameters can be found in the distribution as
.I config/resman.conf.example
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
All configuration options can be overridden by environment variables
with the same name. Example:
.sp
.nf
LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG resman \-\-config /etc/resman.conf
.fi
.SH LOG FILES
.I /var/log/resman.log
.br
The log file is automatically rotated when it reaches the maximum size
configured in
.B LOG_MAX_SIZE.
Rotation creates a backup file with .1 extension.
.SH STATE FILES
.I /var/run/resman-cgroups.txt
.br
Tracks created cgroups to enable cleanup after restart.
.SH PROMETHEUS METRICS
When enabled, the daemon exposes metrics at http://HOST:PORT/metrics
.IP \(bu 2
resman_cpu_total_usage_percent \- Total CPU usage
.IP \(bu
resman_cpu_user_usage_percent \- Non\-system user CPU usage
.IP \(bu
resman_memory_usage_megabytes \- Total system memory usage
.IP \(bu
resman_active_users_count \- Number of active non\-system users
.IP \(bu
resman_limited_users_count \- Users with active limits
.IP \(bu
resman_limits_active \- Limits status (1=active, 0=inactive)
.IP \(bu
resman_system_load_average \- System load average (1 minute)
.IP \(bu
resman_user_cpu_usage_percent{uid, username} \- CPU usage per user
.IP \(bu
resman_user_memory_usage_bytes{uid, username} \- Memory usage per user (bytes)
.IP \(bu
resman_user_io_read_bytes{uid, username} \- IO read bytes per user (when IO limits enabled)
.IP \(bu
resman_user_io_write_bytes{uid, username} \- IO write bytes per user
.IP \(bu
resman_user_io_read_ops{uid, username} \- IO read operations per user
.IP \(bu
resman_user_io_write_ops{uid, username} \- IO write operations per user
.IP \(bu
resman_user_process_count{uid, username} \- Number of processes per user
.IP \(bu
resman_user_cpu_limited{uid, username} \- User limit status (1=limited, 0=unlimited)
.IP \(bu
resman_limits_activated_total \- Total limit activations (counter)
.IP \(bu
resman_limits_deactivated_total \- Total limit deactivations (counter)
.IP \(bu
resman_control_cycle_duration_seconds \- Control cycle duration (histogram)
.IP \(bu
resman_errors_total{component, error_type} \- Errors by component (counter)
.PP
All user-specific metrics include
.B uid
and
.B username
labels for easy filtering and aggregation in Grafana dashboards.
Since v1.17.0, per-user metrics also include
.B is_limited
label to distinguish monitored vs limited users.
.PP
Example queries:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Sum of all user memory:
.I sum(resman_user_memory_usage_bytes)
.IP \(bu
Top 5 users by CPU:
.I topk(5, resman_user_cpu_usage_percent)
.IP \(bu
Processes per user:
.I resman_user_process_count{username="francesco"}
.IP \(bu
Only limited users:
.I resman_user_cpu_usage_percent{is_limited="true"}
.RE
.SH MCP SERVER (MODEL CONTEXT PROTOCOL)
When enabled, the daemon exposes an MCP server for AI assistant integration.
The MCP server provides tools and resources for querying system status and generating reports.
.PP
Available MCP tools:
.IP \(bu 2
.B get_system_status
\- Current CPU/memory status with hostname
.IP \(bu
.B get_user_metrics
\- Per-user CPU, memory, and process metrics
.IP \(bu
.B get_active_users
\- List of active non-system users
.IP \(bu
.B get_limits_status
\- CPU limits status and details
.IP \(bu
.B get_cgroup_info
\- Cgroup information for a specific user
.IP \(bu
.B get_configuration
\- Current daemon configuration
.IP \(bu
.B get_control_history
\- Recent control cycle history
.IP \(bu
.B get_cpu_report
\- Comprehensive CPU usage report (formatted text)
.IP \(bu
.B get_mem_report
\- Comprehensive memory usage report (formatted text)
.IP \(bu
.B activate_limits
\- Manually activate CPU limits (requires MCP_ALLOW_WRITE_OPS=true)
.IP \(bu
.B deactivate_limits
- Manually deactivate limits (requires MCP_ALLOW_WRITE_OPS=true)
.IP \(bu
.B get_user_history
- Historical CPU/RAM metrics for a specific user (requires METRICS_DB_ENABLED=true)
.IP \(bu
.B get_system_history
- Historical system metrics (requires METRICS_DB_ENABLED=true)
.IP \(bu
.B get_user_summary
- Aggregated statistics (avg/min/max) for a user (requires METRICS_DB_ENABLED=true)
.IP \(bu
.B get_metrics_database_info
- Database status and information (requires METRICS_DB_ENABLED=true)
.PP
All metric outputs include a
.B hostname
field for multi-server environment identification.
.PP
MCP resources (URI-based access):
.IP \(bu 2
resman://system/status
.IP \(bu
resman://users/active
.IP \(bu
resman://limits/status
.IP \(bu
resman://config
.IP \(bu
resman://users/{uid}/metrics
.IP \(bu
resman://cgroups/{uid}
.PP
Example MCP configuration:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Enable MCP:
.I MCP_ENABLED=true
.IP \(bu
Transport mode:
.I MCP_TRANSPORT=stdio
(or
.IR http )
.IP \(bu
HTTP port (for http transport):
.I MCP_HTTP_PORT=8080
.IP \(bu
Allow write operations:
.I MCP_ALLOW_WRITE_OPS=false
.RE
.SH LIMIT HOOKS
When
.B LIMIT_HOOK_ENABLED
is true, ResMan can run an external script, call a webservice, or both whenever
a user is newly limited.
.PP
Script hooks are configured with
.B LIMIT_HOOK_SCRIPT
and receive the following environment variables:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
RESMAN_LIMIT_UID
.IP \(bu
RESMAN_LIMIT_USERNAME
.IP \(bu
RESMAN_LIMIT_CPU_USAGE
.IP \(bu
RESMAN_LIMIT_LIMITED_USERS
.IP \(bu
RESMAN_LIMIT_SHARED_CGROUP
.IP \(bu
RESMAN_LIMIT_TIMESTAMP
.IP \(bu
RESMAN_LIMIT_SERVER_ROLE
.RE
.PP
Webservice hooks are configured with
.B LIMIT_HOOK_URL
and receive an HTTP POST with a JSON payload containing uid, username,
cpu_usage, limited_users, shared_cgroup, timestamp, source, and server_role.
.PP
Hook execution is asynchronous and bounded by
.B LIMIT_HOOK_TIMEOUT
seconds.
.SH SIGNALS
.B SIGHUP
\- Reload configuration
.br
.B SIGINT, SIGTERM
\- Graceful shutdown
.SH EXAMPLES
Start with custom configuration:
.sp
.nf
resman \-\-config /etc/my\-config.conf
.fi
.sp
Start with debug logging:
.sp
.nf
LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG resman
.fi
.sp
Check version:
.sp
.nf
resman \-\-version
.fi
.SH SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS
.IP \(bu 2
Linux kernel 4.5+ (cgroups v2)
.IP \(bu
Write access to /sys/fs/cgroup
.IP \(bu
Root privileges or CAP_SYS_ADMIN capability
.IP \(bu
Go runtime (if running from source)
